00:47:39.919 --> 00:47:41.919
Like that is the cheap and easy part.

00:47:41.919 --> 00:47:50.919
The hard thing is validating correctness, you know, thinking hard about the architecture,

00:47:50.919 --> 00:47:53.919
like all these things that come downstream of writing code.

00:47:53.919 --> 00:47:58.919
And so increasingly what we see is like, you know, interaction that like,

00:47:58.919 --> 00:48:00.919
I don't really know what we do about this, but it just doesn't really make sense,

00:48:00.919 --> 00:48:07.919
is like we have an issue, a contributor takes it, they just, you know, drop it into Cloud Code

00:48:07.919 --> 00:48:09.919
and say like fix and link to the issue.

00:48:09.919 --> 00:48:11.919
And then they just put up the PR, right?

00:48:11.919 --> 00:48:14.919
And then it's like, what's the, no, but it's sort of like, what's the point of that?

00:48:14.919 --> 00:48:18.919
Because like I could just do that, right?

00:48:18.919 --> 00:48:21.919
And the hard part is what happens after, which is we have a bunch of,

00:48:21.919 --> 00:48:23.919
we have to give a bunch of feedback, we have to think hard about the change,

00:48:23.919 --> 00:48:25.919
we have to think hard about how you validate it.

00:48:25.919 --> 00:48:31.919
And, you know, if the person who puts it up hasn't done that work or thought about doing that work,

00:48:31.919 --> 00:48:33.919
like that's actually, that is like the hard part, right?

00:48:33.919 --> 00:48:35.919
It's like I can prompt the agent.

00:48:35.919 --> 00:48:39.919
A lot of like, you know, I guess I call them slop PRs, you know, and so like I've even heard.

00:48:39.919 --> 00:48:40.919
Well-intentioned.

00:48:40.919 --> 00:48:41.919
Yeah, well-intentioned.

00:48:41.919 --> 00:48:43.919
Often, often well-intentioned.

00:48:43.919 --> 00:48:49.919
But it's like, you know, if someone, it does create a weird dynamic because for us it's like we get a huge PR,

00:48:49.919 --> 00:48:53.919
we kind of have to like think through like, well, how do we engage with this?

00:48:53.919 --> 00:48:57.919
Like is the person going to engage if we ask them hard follow-up questions?

00:48:57.919 --> 00:49:01.919
Or maybe they're like, you know, we have all these questions like, well, what should I do next?

00:49:01.919 --> 00:49:04.919
And we're like, well, that's actually the hard part is like we don't really know what you should do next.

00:49:04.919 --> 00:49:08.919
Like you have to kind of like do the work of figuring out like how do we develop confidence in the change.

00:49:08.919 --> 00:49:13.919
And so I think, you know, we're sort of trying to figure out like how to, it's not,

00:49:13.919 --> 00:49:17.919
and it's not even exclusive to open source contributors.

00:49:17.919 --> 00:49:19.919
There are like elements of this too that happen like within the team.

00:49:19.919 --> 00:49:24.919
Like I got some feedback, which I thought, which I really appreciated,

00:49:24.919 --> 00:49:31.919
which was that people on the team felt like they couldn't trust my PRs as much anymore,

00:49:31.919 --> 00:49:36.919
which is like completely fair, completely fair and very interesting.

00:49:36.919 --> 00:49:41.919
Because the point was like, you know, previously when people were reviewing my changes within the team,

00:49:41.919 --> 00:49:43.919
you know, they didn't feel like they had to review them super closely.

00:49:43.919 --> 00:49:45.919
Like they trusted my work a lot.

00:49:45.919 --> 00:49:48.919
And now it's like if I'm putting up a PR that's done by Cloud Code,

00:49:48.919 --> 00:49:56.919
like I am, like empirically I'm putting up code that has patterns or mistakes or issues in it

00:49:56.919 --> 00:49:58.919
that I just wouldn't have put up before.

00:49:58.919 --> 00:50:02.919
Do you feel like your trust or confidence in your PRs stayed the same?

00:50:02.919 --> 00:50:04.919
Like, no, I mean definitely gone down.

00:50:04.919 --> 00:50:05.919
Fair.

00:50:05.919 --> 00:50:09.919
Like I think I'm still a lot more productive, but like this is why it's like,

00:50:09.919 --> 00:50:12.919
I think it's like a very challenging moment to like figure out how to think about these things.

00:50:12.919 --> 00:50:18.919
Like I, you know, and sometimes too I'm like, you know, a bunch of stuff gets pointed out on a PR.

00:50:18.919 --> 00:50:23.919
Like, sorry, what it took for me to realize this by the way was I put up a PR

00:50:23.919 --> 00:50:27.919
and I will try to review my PRs myself first,

00:50:27.919 --> 00:50:31.919
but it's a little different when it's code that you've been close to and like writing.

00:50:31.919 --> 00:50:35.919
But I put up a PR and I thought it was like fine.

00:50:35.919 --> 00:50:41.919
And then I got like a lot of feedback from someone on our team who's great.

00:50:42.919 --> 00:50:46.919
And, you know, he like looked at it really closely and he gave me like a lot of like real feedback.

00:50:46.919 --> 00:50:48.919
He's like, this is like not, like this is unused.

00:50:48.919 --> 00:50:50.919
Like this is, why are we doing this here?

00:50:50.919 --> 00:50:52.919
Like why aren't we using the implementation we have from over here?

00:50:52.919 --> 00:50:54.919
All these problems that I hadn't really noticed.

00:50:54.919 --> 00:50:58.919
And so like getting a review from someone who wasn't using an agent at all

00:50:58.919 --> 00:51:01.919
and was a domain expert and was thinking really carefully about it.

00:51:01.919 --> 00:51:05.919
Like I've just had to, over time I'm trying to build up the philosophy

00:51:05.919 --> 00:51:07.919
that I'm still responsible for my own code.

00:51:07.919 --> 00:51:12.919
Because it's very easy to forget that when the agents are just like turning stuff out

00:51:12.919 --> 00:51:13.919
and you're like this looks good.

00:51:13.919 --> 00:51:17.919
Yeah, I mean lately like I've been on this journey of essentially, you know,

00:51:17.919 --> 00:51:21.919
I think I'm also in the same place that you are now where like I'm primarily using,

00:51:21.919 --> 00:51:24.919
you know, primarily using cloud code to implement.

00:51:24.919 --> 00:51:27.919
So like my workflow is I have a bunch of stack terminals,

00:51:27.919 --> 00:51:31.919
usually three or four or five cloud code sessions.

00:51:31.919 --> 00:51:34.919
I work on different projects in parallel because, you know,

00:51:34.919 --> 00:51:37.919
while I'm busy working on one thing, I can work on something else.

00:51:37.919 --> 00:51:40.919
And so like I've enjoyed like the productivity benefit of being able to like

00:51:40.919 --> 00:51:43.919
nudge along work and on multiple things or like multiple, you know,

00:51:43.919 --> 00:51:46.919
work trees within the same project.

00:51:46.919 --> 00:51:50.919
But like, you know, like you, like I've run into the same problem of the code quality

00:51:50.919 --> 00:51:54.919
just being, you know, often poor, surprising.

00:51:54.919 --> 00:51:58.919
I mean it has certainly gotten a lot better, but there's like this like

00:51:58.919 --> 00:52:03.919
code quality problem either of like solving the problem in a much more verbose way

00:52:03.919 --> 00:52:06.919
or with a lot of code duplication, like copy and pasting the same thing,

00:52:06.919 --> 00:52:10.919
especially like the test suites end up like much bigger and much more bloated

00:52:10.919 --> 00:52:11.919
and duplicated.

00:52:11.919 --> 00:52:14.919
And I'm like one of these, I'm like obsessed with like code cleanliness

00:52:14.919 --> 00:52:17.919
and like not repeating yourself and not having code duplication.

00:52:17.919 --> 00:52:19.919
And so like, you know, code smells.

00:52:19.919 --> 00:52:20.919
I built a lintel.

00:52:20.919 --> 00:52:22.919
Yeah, you know a thing or two about this.

00:52:22.919 --> 00:52:25.919
Yeah, so whenever I open up these code bases, I look at the PR.

00:52:25.919 --> 00:52:28.919
I'm like, ooh, this is like, you know, as far as code smells, like this is,

00:52:28.919 --> 00:52:32.919
you know, stinky, stinky cheese level of code smell.

00:52:33.919 --> 00:52:38.919
But, you know, I feel like there's certainly like the human element of code review

00:52:38.919 --> 00:52:39.919
is important.

00:52:39.919 --> 00:52:44.919
And I think like for you, the agent user, I think part of it is your responsibility

00:52:44.919 --> 00:52:49.919
to like, you know, do as much of that before putting a PR so that you aren't

00:52:49.919 --> 00:52:55.919
like essentially asking other people to do all of the review labor.

00:52:55.919 --> 00:52:58.919
And so like I've been trying to figure out how to do that.

00:52:59.919 --> 00:53:03.919
I've also been investing a lot in like what I call adversarial code review tools

00:53:03.919 --> 00:53:08.919
because if you ask Quad Code to review its own code that it just generated,

00:53:08.919 --> 00:53:11.919
like you just do slash review, it's going to be like, looks great,

00:53:11.919 --> 00:53:13.919
ready for production, you know.

00:53:13.919 --> 00:53:15.919
And then if you're like, no, it's not, you're like, you're absolutely right.

00:53:15.919 --> 00:53:17.919
I need to write more test cases.

00:53:17.919 --> 00:53:20.919
And so I think we've all been through that like gaslighting of the agent's

00:53:20.919 --> 00:53:23.919
overconfidence and self-confidence in its work.

00:53:23.919 --> 00:53:26.919
So I think just to connect these two things, I think it's so interesting,

00:53:27.919 --> 00:53:31.919
people on your team who are like, I feel less confident in your PRs

00:53:31.919 --> 00:53:33.919
and you're like, maybe me too.

00:53:33.919 --> 00:53:34.919
It's just a lot more.

00:53:34.919 --> 00:53:36.919
I'm like, that's totally fair.

00:53:36.919 --> 00:53:41.919
And Wes saying like, exploring like this idea of adversarial reviews,

00:53:41.919 --> 00:53:45.919
like is there a way to like up the confidence and the quality?

00:53:45.919 --> 00:53:46.919
Yeah.

00:53:46.919 --> 00:53:47.919
I'm really curious.

00:53:47.919 --> 00:53:49.919
I think it connects back to something you said on Twitter,

00:53:49.919 --> 00:53:53.919
like that reviewing code is the hard part.

00:53:54.919 --> 00:53:59.919
We're not very good at like understanding code quality, I think, as humans.

00:53:59.919 --> 00:54:06.919
And like, I think, well, I mean, I guess like the mentality I try to take

00:54:06.919 --> 00:54:12.919
towards some of this stuff is like, one, if we put something up and it's,

00:54:12.919 --> 00:54:17.919
well, first of all, it's, I feel like the thing where you have a cloud code

00:54:17.919 --> 00:54:20.919
session that writes the code and then you create a separate session

00:54:20.919 --> 00:54:23.919
and ask it to review it and it comes up with a bunch of valid feedback,

00:54:23.919 --> 00:54:28.919
it's incredibly unintuitive if you know like nothing about how these work.

00:54:28.919 --> 00:54:30.919
If you don't know anything about how the models work,

00:54:30.919 --> 00:54:32.919
it's incredibly unintuitive that that could ever happen.

00:54:32.919 --> 00:54:35.919
Because you're like, wait a second, it's the same agent.

00:54:35.919 --> 00:54:36.919
Like it wrote the code.

00:54:36.919 --> 00:54:38.919
Like how does it not find these problems?

00:54:38.919 --> 00:54:41.919
And for me, that's actually a good example of trying to develop intuition

00:54:41.919 --> 00:54:44.919
around like how these things are, the limitations that these things have.

00:54:44.919 --> 00:54:46.919
Because it's like, yeah, it actually does kind of make,

00:54:46.919 --> 00:54:48.919
it does make sense if you understand how they work.

00:54:48.919 --> 00:54:52.919
But if you don't and you just view it as, I put things into the model

00:54:52.919 --> 00:54:54.919
and it should like always like do the perfect right thing.

00:54:54.919 --> 00:54:55.919
It's an oracle.

00:54:55.919 --> 00:54:57.919
It's just, it's the truth oracle.

00:54:57.919 --> 00:55:00.919
Yeah, if you view it in a certain way, it's like,

00:55:00.919 --> 00:55:04.919
it's a very good example to me of like how you have to learn to use the tools.

00:55:04.919 --> 00:55:06.919
Yeah, I mean, that's not like a hard thing to learn or to do,

00:55:06.919 --> 00:55:10.919
but it's like, it's very unintuitive that that would be the case,

00:55:10.919 --> 00:55:13.919
in my opinion, if you don't understand how they work.

00:55:13.919 --> 00:55:17.919
I think, I mean, one thing I've tried to like internalize is,

00:55:17.919 --> 00:55:21.919
and we're still like, I would say we as a team don't have answers

00:55:21.919 --> 00:55:22.919
to any of this stuff.

00:55:22.919 --> 00:55:23.919
We're still really trying to figure it out.

00:55:23.919 --> 00:55:26.919
I think for me, again, it's like people need to be responsible

00:55:26.919 --> 00:55:28.919
for their own code.

00:55:28.919 --> 00:55:31.919
When you see the model do things wrong,

00:55:31.919 --> 00:55:36.919
try to find ways to prevent that in the future,

00:55:36.919 --> 00:55:38.919
whether it's like updating the CloudMD or the AgentsMD

00:55:38.919 --> 00:55:41.919
or adding static analysis tooling.

00:55:41.919 --> 00:55:45.919
We're actually probably turning on more Lint rules now than we used to

00:55:45.919 --> 00:55:48.919
because, and we have like, even in Rust, we have like,

00:55:48.919 --> 00:55:50.919
we've always used clippy pedantic.

00:55:50.919 --> 00:55:51.919
It's like the most pedantic.

00:55:51.919 --> 00:55:52.919
We have like a couple of rules disabled.

00:55:52.919 --> 00:55:55.919
So like try to enforce things programmatically because the model's good

00:55:55.919 --> 00:55:58.919
at following if you have something that's enforced programmatically

00:55:58.919 --> 00:56:02.919
and it's getting diagnostics about it, it will fix those things.

00:56:02.919 --> 00:56:05.919
Or try to give feedback in the CloudMD or similar.

00:56:05.919 --> 00:56:07.919
Like we had all these problems.

00:56:07.919 --> 00:56:10.919
They're not like problems, but it was like, you know, in Python,

00:56:10.919 --> 00:56:13.919
oh, like Cloud kept adding like dunder all to like all these things

00:56:13.919 --> 00:56:15.919
and it's like we basically never want to use that.

00:56:15.919 --> 00:56:16.919
And like blah, blah, blah.

00:56:16.919 --> 00:56:20.919
Or in Rust, it was like, oh, it's not using let, like let chains,

00:56:20.919 --> 00:56:22.919
which are like a very new feature.

00:56:22.919 --> 00:56:24.919
And so probably not as much of it in the training data

00:56:24.919 --> 00:56:26.919
or it doesn't realize it has access to them.

00:56:26.919 --> 00:56:29.919
So like putting that in the CloudMD.

00:56:29.919 --> 00:56:33.919
And then over time, like trying to bolster, I mean,

00:56:33.919 --> 00:56:36.919
this was important even before AI, but it's like trying to bolster,

00:56:36.919 --> 00:56:39.919
like how can we get confidence in changes, you know, faster?

00:56:39.919 --> 00:56:43.919
Like in, you know, in TY, for example, we have this,

00:56:43.919 --> 00:56:47.919
we invested a lot in this like ecosystem report infrastructure.

00:56:47.919 --> 00:56:51.919
So like every time we put up a change, we run over a bunch of projects

00:56:51.919 --> 00:56:55.919
and we have like a really nice report that diffs all the diagnostics

00:56:55.919 --> 00:56:58.919
and links to the lines of code and like helps you understand what's going on.

00:56:58.919 --> 00:57:02.919
And like, and that's really helpful for building confidence in changes

00:57:02.919 --> 00:57:04.919
because we can like click through that report and like see what changed

00:57:04.919 --> 00:57:07.919
and try to identify problems.

00:57:07.919 --> 00:57:10.919
Ironically, also a thing that's incredibly useful

00:57:10.919 --> 00:57:15.919
is you give Claude that report and you ask it,

00:57:15.919 --> 00:57:17.919
are these false positives or false negatives?

00:57:17.919 --> 00:57:18.919
Go analyze the code.

00:57:18.919 --> 00:57:23.919
Like we've probably saved, we're saving like hours and hours and hours on that.

00:57:23.919 --> 00:57:25.919
Like try and understand whether these changes are false positives

00:57:25.919 --> 00:57:27.919
or false negatives, or like we get this user report,

00:57:27.919 --> 00:57:29.919
come up with a very minimal reproduction.

00:57:29.919 --> 00:57:31.919
Like someone on our team yesterday was like,

00:57:31.919 --> 00:57:33.919
I think this would have taken me six hours before.

00:57:33.919 --> 00:57:36.919
And so, you know, that's, I guess another lesson is like

00:57:36.919 --> 00:57:38.919
trying to find things that are off the critical path,

00:57:38.919 --> 00:57:42.919
that aren't shipping production code that you can automate.

00:57:42.919 --> 00:57:44.919
Yeah, and I've discovered just through trial and error

00:57:44.919 --> 00:57:46.919
that different agents are better at different things.

00:57:46.919 --> 00:57:48.919
Like for me, like the stuff that I'm working on,

